\begin_layout Section
The model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model used is a Wright-Fisher model (also depicted in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Wright-Fisher-model"

\end_inset

) that follows the inheritance of an allele in a constant-size population
 of random-mating haploid individuals.
 The term 'random mating' does not fully apply, as the individuals are haploid.
 What is the case, is that paernts create offsping, of which only a certain
 constant number survive to reproduce.
 The generations are strictly separated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Derivation of the likelihood
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume four individuals sampled (
\begin_inset Formula $n=4$
\end_inset

)(see also table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Symbol-descriptions"

\end_inset

) from a much larger population (
\begin_inset Formula $N\gg n$
\end_inset

) being at present time (
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

).
 These four haploid individuals have a parent, yet, together, they may have
 one single to four different parents.
 Assuming a large population (
\begin_inset Formula $N\gg n$
\end_inset

) we can expect either zero or one coalescent event (that is: the four individua
ls have either four or three different parents).
 When assigning parents to the focal individuals, there are three ways a
 coalescence can take place: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
when assigning the second parent, which might be the first individual's
 parent as well.
 This equals the chance of the second coalescing with the first (
\begin_inset Formula $1/N$
\end_inset

) multiplied by the chance the third individual does not coalesce (
\begin_inset Formula $1-(1/N)$
\end_inset

) multiplied by the chance the fourth individual does not coalesce (
\begin_inset Formula $1-(2/N)$
\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{i=2}(n=4,N,t=1)=\left(\frac{1}{N}\right)\left(1-\frac{1}{N}\right)\left(1-\frac{2}{N}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
when assigning the third parent, which might be the first or second individual's
 parent as well
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{i=3}(n=4,N,t=1)=\left(1-\frac{1}{N}\right)\left(\frac{2}{N}\right)\left(1-\frac{2}{N}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
when assigning the fourth parent, which might be the first,second or third
 individual's parent as well
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{i=4}(n=4,N,t=1)=\left(1-\frac{1}{N}\right)\left(1-\frac{2}{N}\right)\left(\frac{3}{N}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Summing these results in the chance there will be a coalescent event between
 now and the previous generation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(n=4,N,t=1)=\left(\frac{1}{N}\right)\left(1-\frac{1}{N}\right)\left(1-\frac{2}{N}\right)+\left(1-\frac{1}{N}\right)\left(\frac{2}{N}\right)\left(1-\frac{2}{N}\right)+\left(1-\frac{1}{N}\right)\left(1-\frac{2}{N}\right)\left(\frac{3}{N}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This equation is for 4 lineages.
 This can be generalized for n lineages.
 First extract the common pattern from the equation above:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(n=4,N,t=1)=\left(\frac{1}{N}\right)\prod_{i=1}^{n-2}\left(1-\frac{i}{N}\right)+\left(\frac{2}{N}\right)\prod_{i=1}^{n-2}\left(1-\frac{i}{N}\right)+\left(\frac{3}{N}\right)\prod_{i=1}^{n-2}\left(1-\frac{i}{N}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(n,N)=\sum_{j=1}^{n-1}\left[\left(\frac{j}{N}\right)\prod_{i=1}^{n-2}\left(1-\frac{i}{N}\right)\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming a large population (
\begin_inset Formula $N\gg n$
\end_inset

), the product term can be left out (
\begin_inset Formula $1-(i/N)=1$
\end_inset

), resulting in
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(n,N,t=1)=\sum_{j=1}^{n-1}\frac{j}{N}=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{j=1}^{n-1}j=\frac{1}{N}.\frac{n(n-1)}{2}=\frac{1}{N}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
2
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If there is a coalencent event t timesteps back in time, this generalizes
 to:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(n,N,t)=\frac{1}{N}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
2
\end{array}\right)\left[1-\frac{1}{N}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
2
\end{array}\right)\right]^{t-1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The discrete time equation at the left-hand side can be approximated by
 the continuous equation at the right-hand side of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:discrete_to_continuous_approximation"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[1-\frac{1}{N}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
2
\end{array}\right)\right]^{t-1}\approx e^{-\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
2
\end{array}\right)\frac{t_{i}}{N}}\label{eq:discrete_to_continuous_approximation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

